CARTE POSTALE
postmark  COLOMBO 6 PM 29 JAN 1929
Mother dear,
This is a picture of the boat we are traveling on to France. It is a nice large boat. There is a swimming pool on it and we have lots of fun in the water. Wish you were with me to enjoy the nice voyage. plenty of fresh air and etc.  Will [unclear] mail some more cards in Colombo.
Lots of love,
Genevieve
Mrs. Grace Brown
Hardinsburg,
Ky.
U.S.A.

pencilled in top margin:  1929
letterhead  P& O.S.N. CO.  S.S.     seal with flags and half-sun with rays.  Quis separabit    U.N.Z.   B.I.  P&O  N.Z

Jan. 25.
Dear Mother,

  I'm on the boat writing this and so far the weather hasn't been rough.  I'm certainly glad, because when the boat rows and pitches I get terribly sick.   This will be mailed in Colombo.   We get in there at Tuesday next and leave the next day at twelve.
  Everyone around is busy playing deck games and etc.   I've been practising quite a bit on my sousaphone.  This boat isn't crowded like most of them, not many  young people around, so you see we do a lot of practising

pencilled in bottom margin:  1929

letterhead  P& O.S.N. CO.  S.S.     seal with flags and half-sun with rays.  Quis separabit    U.N.Z.   B.I.  P&O  N.Z

We give a concert on board to-night.  I hope the old fossils like it.

 I can hardly wait until we arrive in France.   I'm sure everything will be more interesting.   Hope we come home soon - it seems like America is a thing so far away.  I will write and tell  you about Colombo.   Bye, bye, Mother - write me at my England address.  

Lovingly,

[[letterhead]
Canadian Pacific Hotels
Hotel Vancouver  Vancouver B.C.   illustration of hotel building
Wed - 27
Mother dear,
We sailed this noon and I'm going to drop this off in Victoria - I will drop cards in every port and write soon as we reach there - You start mailing letters to Australia, so I will get some there.  When the gang plank pulled up this morning, the orchestra played "Farewell To thee".  It sure gave me a creepy feeling - Please write soon and often -
Lots of love -
Bye -Gente
J.C. Williamson Ltd.
Sydney, Australia
℅ Ingenues
pencilled note in bottom margin   1925

1
[pencilled in top margin]  1929
[[letterhead]   P&O.S.N. CO.  S.S.     seal;  flags and sun  Quis Separabit   U.N.Z.   B.I.   P.&O.  N.Z. 

Dear Mother,

   I'm going to write and tell you about Colombo.  As you probably know, by looking at your map - Colombo is on an island called Ceylon.   the boat having reached there about     1 o'clock in the afternoon, we got off and went into the village.   The wharf was surrounded by the natives, some wearing a piece of cloth draped below their waist and some not so much.   They are a very, very brown class of people, not black like our negroes and some of them can speak a little English.  We visited the Budda temple.  Had to take off our shoes before entering.

[pencilled in bottom margin]  1929

2.
Also passed the Mohammed temple and the carving and architecture on it was simply exquisite.  We went riding in a rickshaw and practically rode all afternoon and it cost only about 72 cents in our money.  The poor natives pulling these rickshaws were very skinny and actually they took the pace of a horse trotting along.   I felt very sorry for them because the sweat poured down from being so hot.   Going up and down the streets you'd see the people walking along with a huge bunch of bananas balanced on their heads, or anything they might happen to be carrying.   Some of the women have rings in their nose and in their ears.   If I lived a hundred years I could never tell you all I saw and how thrilled I was.

[[letterhead]   P&O.S.N. CO.  S.S.     seal;  flags and sun  Quis Separabit   U.N.Z.   B.I.   P.&O.  N.Z. 
I never realized conditions could exist as they are.  Riding thru the park you could see cocanut [sic] trees, banananas [sic] growing here and there.

   When you'd go into a store the dealers would nearly eat you up trying to make a sale.   There are so many of these natives, that some of them don't even get enough to eat, so when a boat comes into port they beg for money and will sell anything to make a penny or a rupee.
  I bought quite a few cards but didn't mail them   Will send them out when I get to France.  Be sure and keep them, because they will be

very interesting to have when I get back home.  To-morrow we reach Bombay and that is in India.  I will write and tell you about it.

  I forgot to tell you I won prize at the fancy dress ball on boat for being the most humorous.  I had part of the make up on like Grace uses and a pair of glasses that made me look as if I were crosseyed.  Everyone said that I looked exactly like Grace in  her dance.
  We played on deck for a dance and the Captain presented us all with a pin with Narkunda, the name of the boar, engraved on it.  I just must close, will write again soon.  Bye - Love to all of you.  Geneiveve B.

[[letterhead]   P&O.S.N. CO.  S.S.     seal;  flags and sun  Quis Separabit   U.N.Z.   B.I.   P.&O.  N.Z. 
Feb. 7-
Dear Mother,
I'm still on the Narkunda - and we have stopped in two ports since I last wrote. I think I told you about Colombo so now I will try and tell you about Bombay. First, Bombay is in India and is a very large city. The people that inhabited the place are mostly parsees, Hindus and Mohammedians. They are also a brown class of people and dress similiar to the people in Colombo. I have a large collection of cards from these towns we are stopping in- thought.

2
first I might mail them, but they might get lost, so I'd rather not take any chance.

 I will try and tell you one very interesting place, we visited in Bombay. It was the Tower of Silence. It is the burying grounds of the Parsees. The Parsee are the richest class of people. These grounds consist of about fifty acres and there is a tower upon entering and they take their dead to the entrance of this crossed out: and then they are placed upon a high and are not allowed to go any farther. The body is then removed to about the center of the field and left for the vultures and birds of all kinds to pick the body to pieces. When we went to

3
[[letterhead]   P&O.S.N. CO.  S.S.     seal;  flags and sun  Quis Separabit   U.N.Z.   B.I.   P.&O.  N.Z. 
the grounds you could see a numerous amount of birds flying around waiting for someone to die. That sounds like a fairy tale and one wouldn't believe it unless they actually saw it. I bought you a lovely gift in Bombay- I know you will like it. I only hope I het home with all of my stuff.

 I will now and tell you about Aden - We stopped in that part yesterday. Aden is in Arabia and a very small town. It is really a town that is in between the hills. Upon approaching the hills on the boat, you never would have any idea, that a

town could be in a place like this. You have to run in thru tunnels and etc. before reaching the main part of the town.  These ports all smell terribly and nearly make you sick. You see plenty of carts drawn by camels. Honestly, you have no idea as to how thrilling these places are. Some of the scenes look like pictures you have seen in books. We visited the tanks and the gardens. Cleopatra was supposed to have taken a bath there. You don't see any greens around Aden - it is a desert country and if they have rain once every two or three years, they are lucky. I bought a souvenir there also a present that I will

[[letterhead]   P&O.S.N. CO.  S.S.     seal;  flags and sun  Quis Separabit   U.N.Z.   B.I.   P.&O.  N.Z. 
probably give to [hole in page]. the most interesting trip of all comes Sunday. We are getting off the boat and go up to Cairo, Egypt. Just think Mother I really get to see the sphinx and the pyramids. Now I will close now and tell you about that trip later. Do write me soon and often - you know Mother I would love to see all of you - it seems that I have been away so long. It will be a year the 21 of June that I sailed. Tell Murray to write - did he get home Xmas. Bye--
Lovingly -
Gente

My dear Mother,
We are in Sao Paulo and played our first show this evening. Our act sure goes over big.
We had a two weeks stay in Reo de Janero and enjoyed it very much. We were at Ambassadors Morgans party - you know the American consul.
There is an American colony here and believe me Mother we were entertained royally by them.They gave a big social out at the country club for us and everything was done up in the latest of style. They all seemed so proud of us. I had a little Brazilian friend that spoke nice English who took me out a bit. He had a chrysler.

letterhead  Bristol Hotel   9 de Julio y Rivera Indarte  Cordoba telefonos:  Gerencia 5252  Porteria  5008   L. Dist.  5020
written in pencil in top margin:  1929
Dear Mother,
I received your letter yesterday and it sure made me happy. Just homesick for any mail from home and do Mother please write me often - doesn't Franky ever have any time to write. We are busy getting the act either ready for the States or Europe. As yet we have quite a few more weeks down here. 

  Well, your letter was quite newsy - all the old cronies are marrying. Here's hoping they will all be happy. The more I see of the world the less I think of matrimony. So Mildred was in H-Burg. I would like to see her. Has she changed. By the way do any of the kids have long hair yet? I also received Pauline's announcement, I will send her something from here or Europe and drop her a few lines.  What does the husband look like? young or old; rich or poor? Where is Don Walker, Murray Beard - Ray Hall - Aren't they engaged yet or aren't rumors out about them? Is Miriam's husband a native of H-Burg - Where does Cat's friend hail from.
  I suppose you wonder how South America is coming. I can't say I'd ever live here, not even if I ever cared for a fellow down here. We

pencilled in bottom margin   1929

letterhead  Bristol Hotel   9 de Julio y Rivera Indarte  Cordoba telefonos:  Gerencia 5252  Porteria  5008   L. Dist.  5020

are playing this week in a very small town called Cordoba.  The oldest place in S.A.   The streets are very narrow and the whole lay of the city rather reminds me of Cairo, Egypt. We are to he here only a week - go back to Buenos Aires for a return engagement, then Rio and then?? I hope the States but don't plan on it.
By the way you know it is winter here and I'm wearing my heavy coat. Did you know since we have left the States we have practically had nothing but winters - Had winter in Australia, winter in Europe, and winter down here and no matter where we go from here we will find another winter. Sure are tired of cold weather. of course in Rio we have some tropical weather.
[Signature cut off]

letterhead seal with leaves and two dolphins pointing at a globe with arrows through it  FLAMENGO HOTEL  106 PRAIA DO FLAMENGO RIO DE JANEIRO
in pencil in top margin  1929
Reio de Janeiro
Dear Mother,
To-day finds the Ingenues in Rio de Janeiro and we are quite a sensation here. Another week here and we go to Buenos Aires. So many Americans have been here to see us. One man from Tennessee came back to see me. He is arranging for an outing for six of us. We are going to the American Ambassador's house Sunday nite to dance. He came back to see all of us last week. 

  This city is beautiful, very tropical.  Well, Mother, write me soon and tell me all of the news.

Love, 
Jenny
Teatro Maipo
Beunos Aires,
Argentina  S.A.
℅ Ingenues

Mother dear, 

  We are on our way to Eng. so send our mail to the Paris address. Don't know when we will come home - nothing definite. All are well and I am enjoying life immensely - At last found a man I could love - only to leave him- 100% perfect. Couldn't make up my mind to stay here. Hope I don't regret it.   If I do stay, will let you know.   If I weren't so far from home and you mother dear. Bye-bye- Love Jene-

At  Waikiki Beach, Honolulu

POST CARD  Published exclusively by The Paradise Postcard Co. Box 3461, Honolulu H.T.
Fringed by graceful coconut palms is the famous beach of Waikiki, some four miles from Honolulu..Here can be enjoyed a swim every day of he year, for the temperature of the water averages 78 degress from January to December, and thanks to the protection afforded by a coral reef, there is no fear of sharks or undertow.
postmark  HONOLULU HAWAII  JUL 5  9 30 AM  1928
July 4-
Arrived in Honolulu July 3 around 4 o'clock. Mother dear, it is wonderful. It is positively the most romantic place I've ever been in. Since I've gotten off the boat I feel great- We went site seeing and swimming at Wakiki [sic] Beach last nite. You just can't imagine how thrilled I am. It is really is the only place that I've ever been in that I haven't been disappointed. I'm will write a letter and mail in next port
Bye -  Write soon-
Love-
Gents
Mrs. Gus Browne
Hardinsburg -
Ky.
U.S.A.
